{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"604d1dd6-4c24-4a24-a938-6e51afa53ec5","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing your crash dump. Here are the main tools for .NET dump analysis:\n\n**`dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform):\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\nUseful SOS commands inside the analyzer:\n- `clrstack` — managed call stack of the crashing thread\n- `pe` (`printexception`) — print the last exception\n- `dumpheap -stat` — heap summary (for OOM crashes)\n- `threads` — list all managed threads\n- `setthread <id>` + `clrstack` — inspect other threads\n\n**`lldb` with SOS** (Linux):\n```bash\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n# or\nlldb --core your-file.dmp\n```\n\n**WinDbg/Visual Studio** (Windows):\n- Open the `.dmp` in Visual Studio or WinDbg for a full debugging experience.\n\n**Typical workflow:**\n1. Run `dotnet-dump analyze <file>.dmp`\n2. Run `pe` to check for an unhandled exception\n3. Run `clrstack` to see what the crashing thread was doing\n4. Use `threads` → `setthread` → `clrstack` to examine other threads if needed\n\nWould you like me to run `dotnet-dump analyze` on your file if it's accessible on this machine?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"760d8c62-0615-490b-b5a8-184006c64d38","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description explicitly says:\n\n- USE FOR: enabling automatic crash dumps, capturing dumps, setting up dump collection\n- DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze\n\nSo the dump-collect skill is NOT appropriate here since the user wants to analyze a dump, not collect one.\n\nLet me help them directly with guidance on analyzing crash dumps.","outputTokens":477},"id":"a4e9ca32-8402-4497-b29e-173c929bde7a","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:05:51.470Z","parentId":"